agent-worker  | [AuditWorker Debug] Batch count: 10. First item type: <class 'dict'>. Content: {'event_id': 'dff6d073-069c-4f3b-8ad4-3962369c9f29', 'schema_version': '1', 'event_type': 'chain_end', 'event_time': '1769335624.7184536', 'run_id': '5ba61b94-a359-4f2c-9eab-4cab9ea8f310', 'session_id': 'fe8c3317-bdef-4bae-b154-d75215685387', 'thread_id': '58294cb8-6e9b-47a6-b34d-49e4dc9e1f95', 'span_id': '019bf49e-f981-7df0-88e7-3fb196ba59e4', 'parent_span_id': '', 'component': 'chain', 'actor_type': 'agent', 'actor_id': 'worker', 'payload_json': '{"outputs_digest": "{\'generated_sql\': \\"SELECT m_cities.name, SUM(m_orders.amount) AS total_sales\\\\nFROM m_cities\\\\nJOIN m_customers ON m_cities.id = m_customers.city_id\\\\nJOIN m_orders ON m_customers.id = m_orders.customer_id\\\\nWHERE m_orders.status = \'paid\'\\\\nGROUP BY m_cities.name;\\", \'messages\': [{\'content\': \'<think>Okay, let\\\\\'s see. The user wants the sales data for each city, including the city name and the total sales amount.\\\\n\\\\nFirst, I need to figure out which tables are involved. The cities are in m_cities. Then, the customers are linked to cities via city_id in m_customers. Orders are linked to customers via customer_id in m_orders. So to get sales by city, I need to join m_cities with m_customers, then m_customers with m_orders.\\\\n\\\\nWait, the sales amount is in m_orders.amount. So the steps are:\\\\n\\\\n1. Join m_cities to m_customers on m_cities.id = m_customers.city_id.\\\\n2. Then join m_customers to m_orders on m_customers.id = m_orders.customer_id.\\\\n3. Sum the amount from m_orders for each city.\\\\n\\\\nBut need to check the foreign keys. The foreign key for m_customers is city_id referencing m_cities.id. And m_orders has customer_id referencing m_customers.id. So the correct joins are:\\\\n\\\\nm_cities → m_customers (city_id = m_cities.id)\\\\nm_customers → m_orders (id = customer_id)\\\\n\\\\nSo the query should select m_cities.name and sum(m_orders.amount), grouped by m_cities.name (since it\\\\\'s a dimension column).\\\\n\\\\nWait, but the problem says \\"各城市的销售额数据\\", so each city\\\\\'s total sales. So group by city name.\\\\n\\\\nBut in SQL, when grouping, all non-aggregated columns must be in GROUP BY. So the SELECT clause will have m_cities.name and SUM(m_orders.amount), and GROUP BY m_cities.name.\\\\n\\\\nWait, but maybe the city_id is the primary key, but the user wants city name. So yes, group by m_cities.name.\\\\n\\\\nCheck the tables:\\\\n\\\\nm_cities has id and name. m_customers has city_id. m_orders has customer_id and amount.\\\\n\\\\nSo the join order:\\\\n\\\\nSELECT m_cities.name, SUM(m_orders.amount) AS total_sales\\\\nFROM m_cities\\\\n"}'}
