roblem doesn\\\\\'t specify, but in standard SQL, maybe using EXTRACT(YEAR FROM created_at) and EXTRACT(MONTH FROM created_at), then concatenate. But some databases use DATE_FORMAT(created_at, \\\\\'%Y-%m\\\\\'). Let me check common practices. For MySQL, DATE_FORMAT(created_at, \\\\\'%Y-%m\\\\\') is common. But since the problem says \\"按城市和月份统计订单总金额\\", and the user probably expects using a standard approach.\\\\n\\\\nWait, the sample rows for m_orders have created_at as \\"2023-01-05 00:00:00\\", so the date is in the format YYYY-MM-DD. So formatting to YYYY-MM would be using SUBSTRING or DATE_FORMAT.\\\\n\\\\nBut in SQL, for PostgreSQL, it\\\\\'s TO_CHAR(created_at, \\\\\'YYYY-MM\\\\\'),"}'}
