as customer_id, which links to m_customers.id, and m_customers has city_id which links to m_cities.id.\\\\n\\\\nSo steps: join m_orders to m_customers on customer_id, then join m_customers to m_cities on city_id. Then select the city name from m_cities, format created_at to \\\\\'YYYY-MM\\\\\', sum the amount.\\\\n\\\\nWait, the user\\\\\'s query uses city from orders, but orders doesn\\\\\'t have city. So need to get city via the chain. So the correct join path is orders → customers → cities.\\\\n\\\\nCheck the schema:\\\\n\\\\nm_orders has customer_id → m_customers.id.\\\\n\\\\nm_customers has city_id → m_cities.id.\\\\n\\\\nSo the SQL should join m_orders with m_customers on m_orde", "name": "LangGraph", "langgraph_node": "tools", "subagent": null}'}
