e. Also, the table names are m_orders, not orders. So need to adjust the table names to the schema.\\\\n\\\\nWait, the user provided the schema for tables: m_cities, m_customers, m_orders. So the actual table names are m_cities, m_customers, m_orders. So the query must use these table names.\\\\n\\\\nSo the correct approach:\\\\n\\\\n1. Start with m_orders as the main table.\\\\n\\\\n2. Join m_customers on m_orders.customer_id = m_customers.id.\\\\n\\\\n3. Join m_cities on m_customers.city_id = m_cities.id.\\\\n\\\\nThen select city name from m_cities.name.\\\\n\\\\nGroup by city (m_cities.name), and the month from created_at.\\\\n\\\\nWait, the user\'s sample query uses order", "token_usage": null}'}
