ays \\"月份\\", which is month. So probably the month as \\\\\'YYYY-MM\\\\\' or just the month number. Wait, the sample rows in m_orders have created_at as \\\\\'2023-01-05\\\\\', so the month is part of that.\\\\n\\\\nWait, the user wants the month as part of the result, so we need to extract the month and year from created_at. So maybe using DATE_FORMAT(created_at, \\\\\'%Y-%m\\\\\') to get the month in \\\\\'2023-01\\\\\' format.\\\\n\\\\nThen, join m_orders to m_customers via customer_id, then m_customers to m_cities via city_id. Then group by city name and the month, sum the amount.\\\\n\\\\nWait, but the tables: m_cities has id and name. m_customers has city_id which references m_cities.id. So the city name comes from m_cities.name.\\\\n\\\\nSo", "name": "run_sql", "langgraph_node": "run_sql", "subagent": null}'}
